        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose a single deep continuum observation in band 6 at 233 GHz, with a 
synthesized  beam width of 0.''6, to resolve the inner debris belt around 
Fomalhaut. The requested beam size is a compromise between sensitivity and 
the required resolution to resolve Fomalhaut's inner debris belt and to achieve
the project's science objectives. As discussed in the science justification, the 
inner debris is expected to be located at about 10 AU from the star [26].  
Fomalhaut is 7.7 pc, thus a beam size of 0."6  will achieve a spatial resolution
of 4.6 AU. According to our models, this will clearly detect plausible debris 
morphologies and provide sufficent sensitivity for ensuring the detection of the
inner belt as well as large sections of the outer debris belt.  Our model 
(Fig. 1 and detailed below) suggests that a sensitivity of 12 uJy will achieve 
an S/N~10 at the ansae (projecting ends). This sensitivity is also expected to 
detect large swaths of the outer debris belt as shown in Figure 1. 

We evaluate the detailed sensitivity and resolution requirements through 
simulated ALMA observations. Skymodels are produced following the method 
discussed in Boley et al. [20]. Super-particles are distributed according to 
input morphological constraints. Each super-particle represents an ensemble of 
debris, for which each debris particle is assumed to be comprised of mm-sized 
grains that are in thermal balance with irradiation from the central star
Two million super-particles are used to ensure that the distribution of mass is 
smooth. The resulting model is projected onto a grid with a sky orientation set 
to match Fomalhaut.

Based on compact ALMA cycle 0 observations [20], the outer ring (~140 AU) is 
known to have a FWHM~16 AU. This is corroborated by a null detection in the 
extended cycle 0 data (paper in progress). The outer ring is given its known
offset from the star. The aggregate results of all marginal (unresolved)
detections of the inner belt suggest that most of the inner excess emission is 
located at 10 AU. For this reason, we place an inner ring at 10 AU and scale
the FWHM of the outer debris ring accordingly. The inner ring is assumed to be 
centered about the star for simplicity. 

The combined flux from the two debris rings is set to 33 mJy at 233 GHz, which 
is consistent with Ricci et al.~[18], who found that the flux density for 
Fomalhaut's debris is proportional to the frequency to the 2.7 power (nu^2.7). 
The cycle 0 ALMA observations suggest that there is an excess of about 4.4 mJy
at 350 GHz.  Assuming a stellar photospheric flux density of 2.5 mJy at 350 GHz
[17], the excess is 1.9 mJy at 350 GHz, which, following nu^2.7, scales to 
0.63 mJy at 233 GHz.  Scaling the stellar photosphere by a black body (nu^2), 
the stellar emission at 233 GHz should be 1.1 mJy, which gives a total 
(star+excess) emission of about 1.7 mJy, which is used in the model presented in
Figure 1.

Simulated observations were carried out using CASA 4.2 with the tasks simobserve 
and clean. Antenna file C34-4 was used for generating Figure 1 (beam ~0."6). 
Smaller beam sizes were explored in our models, but the S/N is quickly degraded 
due to surface brightness constraints. For example, a 0."4 beam (antenna file 
C34-5) results in a peak S/N~5 for the inner ring. Attempting to achieve 
sensitivity better than 12 uJy requires impracticable integration times. A beam
size of 0."6 is sufficent for achieving the project science objectives (i-iv)
listed in the science justification. 

Only continuum is requested, so all four spectral windows are set with the large
31.250 MHz channel sizes. The sky frequency is 233 GHz, as is the standard,
optimized setup for band 6 continuum observations.  According to the
ALMA OT, a 12uJy sensitivity can be achieved with about 1.92 hr of on-source
integration, for a total observing time of about 3.86 hr.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
